# üöÄ feature request

 

**This feature request is for @angular/forms**

 

Currently creating a nested `FormGroup` requires knowing its structure in advance. There is unfortunately no capability to dynamically generate a nested `FormGroup` out of a plain `Object`.

 

```

const personFormGroup = new FormGroup({

  name: new FormControl(),

  address: new FormGroup({

    street: new FormControl()

  })

});

 

const personData: object = await someService.fetchPerson();

personFormGroup.patchValue(personData); //or could be `setValue`

 

```

 

It could have been a great feature to generate `FormGroup` or `FormArray` out of a plain `Object` or `Array`, and it seems to me (correct me if I am wrong please) that this should be part of `AbstractControl API`.

 

```

const personData: object = await someService.fetchPerson();

const personAbstractControl: AbstractControl = AbstractControl.from(personData);

```

 

 

For my specific case currently I have created a workaround, method called `mapToAbstractControl`

```

mapToAbstractControl(data: any): AbstractControl {

    if (_isPlainObject(data)) {

      const formGroupDescription = {};

      Object.keys(data).forEach(key => {

        formGroupDescription[key] = this.mapToAbstractControl(data[key]);

      });

      return new FormGroup(formGroupDescription);

    } else if (_isArray(data)) {

      const formArrayDescription = [];

      data.forEach(elem => {

        formArrayDescription.push(this.mapToAbstractControl(elem));

      });

      return new FormArray(formArrayDescription);

    } else {

      return new FormControl(data);

    }

  }

```

 

Do you agree that this method should be part of AbstractControl (e.g. a static method), or am I missing something here?

 

Thanks in advance.

# üöÄ feature request

### Relevant Package
This feature request is for @angular/core


### Description
First off, please let me know if this should actually go into **Issue** first before we confirm it requires a **Feature**

I believe this is closely related to #20810 and am not totally sure if that is necessarily a Bug because, so I wanted to add it as a Feature. I also didn't see any existing Feature request for this particular scenario.

From my understand, Angular components and directives are compiled and rendered in a way so that a given Component will render it's children components and directives before itself.  If this is true than I would expect to be able to work with the `@ContentChildren` and `@ContentChild` APIs to manage descendants of myself within a given component. For example, I want to build a fairly simple Modal component. That Modal component is comprised of a `ModalHeaderComponent` and a `ModalFooterComponent`.  The `ModalFooterComponent` is a super simple component that contains `<ng-content></ng-content>` as its template.

A Modal can take an `@Input() type:string` which is used to pick between a `default`, `warning`, or `error` type of modal (this just changes the color scheme). The Modal also can expect to have a `ButtonDirective` inside of its `ModalFooterComponent` and I always want to make sure the `last` of these `ButtonDirective`s inherits the same `type` as the Modal. 

So here is what I tried:

**ModalComponent**
```
@Component({
    selector: 'sk-modal',
    templateUrl: './modal.component.html',
    styleUrls: ['./modal.component.scss']
})
export class ModalComponent implements AfterContentChecked {

    @Input() type:string;
    @ContentChild(ModalFooterComponent, { static: true }) footer: ModalFooterComponent;

    ... More code...

    ngAfterContentChecked(): void {
        this.footer.btns.last.type = this.type; /* Here this.footer.btns is always undefined! */
    }
```

With this in its template:

```
<sk-modal-footer>
    <ng-content select="[sk-modal-footer]"></ng-content>
</sk-modal-footer>
```

**ModalFooterComponent**
```
@Component({
    selector: 'sk-modal-footer',
    templateUrl: './modal-footer.component.html',
    styleUrls: ['./modal-footer.component.scss'],
    host: {
        class: 'modal-footer'
    }
})
export class ModalFooterComponent implements AfterContentInit {

    @ContentChildren(ButtonDirective, { descendants: true }) btns: QueryList<ButtonDirective>;

    constructor() {

    }

    ngAfterContentInit(): void {
        /* when this is called, this.btns is empty */
    }
}
```

Then my actual implementation of the Modal has this:

**TestModalComponent**
```
<div sk-modal-footer>
    <button sk-button>Cancel</button>
    <button sk-button (click)="doThing()">Ok</button>
</div>
```

I left out a lot of the code, but I think you can get the idea. Basically have a relationship of

```
GreatGrandparent (TestModalComponent) -> Grandparent (ModalComponent) -> Parent (ModalFooterComponent)-> Child (ButtonDirective)
```

where the actual `ButtonDirective` (the Child above) element is given in the `GreatGrandparent` component and transcluded all the way down into the `Parent` is not available in the `GrandParent` and shows up as `undefined`

### Describe the solution you'd like
Have not looked into this yet since I haven't confirmed this something we could support with Angular. Its possible I'm doing this the wrong way.


### Describe alternatives you've considered
I think I can get it working if I access the DOM API directly using `ElementRef`, but then I have to manually wire up all of the change detection.  I imagine Angular should support this capability out of the box somehow.

# üêû bug report

### Is this a regression?

It works as expected in `9.0.0-next.13` with VE but fails with Ivy 

### Description

The following component display a list of users, and has a query list on the divs created.
In `ngAfterViewInit`, we subscribe to the changes and log an `updates` counter every time there is a change. We also trigger a change by replacing the first element in the users array.

```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: '<div *ngFor="let user of users">{{ user.name }}</div>'
})
export class AppComponent implements AfterViewInit {

  updates = 0;
  @ViewChildren('div') divs: QueryList<HTMLDivElement>;

  users = [
    { name: 'Bob' },
    { name: 'Alice' }
  ];

  ngAfterViewInit() {
    this.divs.changes.subscribe(_ => {
      this.updates++;
      console.log(this.updates);
    });
    setTimeout(() => this.users[0] = {name: 'Jen'}, 3000);
  }
}
```

In VE, we can see the counter be logged with a value of 1.
In Ivy, we have no trace: the subscribe is not executed.

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction

Here is a repro https://github.com/cexbrayat/view-children-changes

A unit test checks it:

```typescript
it('should update 1 time', () => {
  const fixture = TestBed.createComponent(AppComponent);
  const app = fixture.componentInstance;
  fixture.detectChanges();

  expect(app.updates).toBe(0);

  // update a user
  app.users[0] = { name: 'Jen' };
  fixture.detectChanges();

  expect(fixture.nativeElement.querySelector('div').textContent).toContain('Jen');
  expect(app.updates).toBe(1);
});
```
This tests runs fine in VE (enableIvy: false in angular.json), but fails with Ivy. To repro:

```
npm i
ng test
# test succeeds
# switch enableIvy to true
ng test
# test fails with Expected 0 to be 1.
```

