The following test will fail in Ivy because `selected` is assigned first and then `value` is assigned which sets selected back to false [here](https://github.com/angular/components/blob/3de0b080282130460a74983dba974f2f2497af96/src/material/list/selection-list.ts#L145). This is because in Ivy, property bindings are set based on the order they appear in the template, not the order they are declared in the component.

```
  const itemValue = 'item1';
  @Component({
      template: `
         <mat-selection-list>
             <mat-list-option [selected]="true" [value]="'${itemValue}'">Item</mat-list-option>
         </mat-selection-list>`
  })
  class SelectionList {}

  const fixture = TestBed.configureTestingModule({declarations: [SelectionList]}).createComponent(SelectionList);
  fixture.detectChanges();
  const listItemEl = fixture.debugElement.query(By.directive(MatListOption))!;
  expect(listItemEl.componentInstance.selected).toBe(true);
  expect(listItemEl.componentInstance.value).toBe(itemValue);
```

I'm not sure how frequently this occurs in this repo, but other components should probably be audited for similar errors if they haven't already.

#### Reproduction

We used Angular Material in our project and it compiles fine with Angular 9.0.0-next.13 (non-Ivy mode). But if we try to set Ivy mode in tsconfig.json:

  "angularCompilerOptions": {
    "enableIvy": true
  },

"ng build --prod" command failed.
We tried two Angular Material versions: 8.2.3 and 9.0.0-next.0 but error still reproduces.

